<br>
Iraq, Iran and North Korea chose to trade in Euros instead of dollars.  This landed them in the Axis of evil.<br>
<br>
Venezuela has decided to start trading oil for commodities, another country not dependent on US dollars.<br>
<br>
Other Opec countries are considering it, especially in light of the crumbling american economy and the devastating corruption in corporate america.<br>
<br>
The only thing worth trading nowadays is oil.  If nobody needs dollars the US can no longer print free, courtesy of the federal reserve...a non US Government corporation, all the dollars it needs to run its massive deficit.<br>
<br>
Think about it.  <br>
<br>
Current estimates of oil reserves at current consumption rates indicate total oil depletion by the year 2030. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 681<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/11/03 11:40:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: It's not about oil</span><hr size=1> &quot;Its about currency. Iraq, Iran and North Korea chose to trade in Euros instead of dollars. This landed them in the Axis of evil.&quot;<br>
<br>
Hmm, ok, why are there no European countries in the axis of evil if all of them use the euro now?<br>
<br>
&quot;Other Opec countries are considering it, especially in light of the crumbling american economy and the devastating corruption in corporate america.&quot;<br>
<br>
Umm, the American economy isn't crumbling.  It's called a recession.  There are natural cycles to the economy.  You can't realistically expect bull markets 100 percent of the time.  It really isn't that bad though.<br>
<br>
&quot;The only thing worth trading nowadays is oil. If nobody needs dollars the US can no longer print free, courtesy of the federal reserve...a non US Government corporation, all the dollars it needs to run its massive deficit.&quot;<br>
<br>
OK, this is just wrong.  Saying this shows a complete lack of understanding of how the economy works.  The federal government does NOT print the money to pay the interest on the national debt.  This would cause absolutely massive inflation.  You would be buying candy bars with wheelbarrows full of ben franklins.  The interest on the national debt is funded by the taxpayers.<br>
<br>
If this were the case the US wouldn't even have a national debt, they'd just print money to buy what they wanted.   However, you can't do this or the value of the dollar drops.  The currency becomes unstable and devalues.  No one will put their money in dollars because of fear that it will become worthless.  Hail, Weimar Republic in the 1930's.<br>
<br>
One of the main reasons that the dollar is still considered the safest place to put your money is that the US has responsible fiscal policy and controls inflation.<br>
<br>
