<br>
There's lots of reasons to take military actions in any part of the world, but should that fact cloud your mind and totally dismiss the possibility that involvement in the middle east isn't primarily about oil and all it's ramifications?  Just because the US has taken action without oil in mind doesn't mean it can't take action with oil interests in mind.<br>
<br>
I agree with Herder indirectly.  I think the reason we weren't so steadfastly stomping around the world taking a more active military role in our foreign oil interests is because our economy--moreover the dollar--wasn't being so heavily rivaled.  With world oil production heading downhill, more dependance on middle east oil looming in the future, and the fact that Iraq's oil is handled in euros now.. if sanctions were lifted it would further jeopardize the US economy; as one of the world's largest oil reserves would be pumping out massive amounts of oil unimpeded and not in our currency.<br>
<br>
Lets ignore that Iraq's oil is traded in euros, lets ignore the US economy is heading downhill, lets ignore the euro is now worth more than the dollar, and lets ignore that Iraq RECENTLY switched to euro exchange.  Now, after 12 years, we're invading on the basis of chemical weapons and human rights?  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>How fucking convenient</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
I don't want to downplay human rights and global security because I think it's definitely worth fighting for and was a major factor in going to war.  However, our world's veins flow with oil, if that oil starts being traded in abundance with any other currency than the dollar and that results in sad times for America.  OPEC could switch currencies if they wanted to, they'd even make more profit, but they don't.  I feel the US is using military might to ensure future control of the oil market in order to remain <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> economic superpower.  I'm not a big economy buff, but the euro pretty much matches the dollar in investments doesn't it?  And if that's true, just about the only thing going for the dollar is its near-monopoly of the oil market.  I wonder if Iraq will still use the euro for its oil exchanges now? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dunnodoncare>Dunnodoncare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 102<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/12/03 1:25:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ok</span><hr size=1> The plan to invade Iraq and even to create an excuse to invade was put forward by Cheney and Wolfowitz back when the first Bush was president.  It got  leaked to the press and the backlash made them drop that plan.  All the information is available from a variety of sources, and PBS's Frontline did a nice series of episodes on the tactics Cheney and company advised and how they compare to the actual methods being used to justify this war.   They admit to it, they speak candidly about their plan in a variety of interviews conducted i